<DOC><DOCNO> AP890707-0198 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-89 0058EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-07 0778</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0811</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Boyd L. Jefferies, who admitted to an illegalstock scheme with inside trader Ivan Boesky, was spared a jail termby a federal judge who praised his cooperation but called WallStreet greed ``absurd and probably obscene.''   U.S. District Judge Morris Lasker sentenced Jefferies on Thursdayto five years probation and fined him $250,000. Jefferies, whopleaded guilty to two felonies, provided information and testimonyin the government's continuing securities fraud investigations inexchange for leniency.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The country's big chain stores reported their sales improvedmodestly in June from May's disappointing results, but the talliesstill indicated consumer spending remains sluggish.   ``The gains were stronger than we had seen in the prior month butacross the board they were certainly not outstanding,'' JosephRonning, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm BrownBrothers Harriman andamp; Co., said of Thursday's figures.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The accounting firms Deloitte Haskins andamp; Sells and Touche Ross andamp;Co. agreed in principle to join forces while two larger Big Eightfirms confirmed they had entered into merger negotiations.   Subject to the approval of partners at Deloitte and Touche Ross,the combined company would have worldwide revenue exceeding $4billion and employ over 65,000 people in 101 countries. It will beknown as Deloitte andamp; Touche in the United States, the firms saidThursday.   Separately, Arthur Andersen andamp; Co. and Price Waterhouse confirmedreports that they had begun talks about a possible merger of theirworldwide operations.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Time Inc. lawyers have charged ParamountCommunications Inc. with trying to deceive the FederalCommunications Commission about how long it would take Paramount tocomplete its $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time.   The media giant's attorneys, in a letter to FCC mass media bureauchief Alex D. Felker released to the media Thursday, accusedParamount of making false statements in applications for approval offormer Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld as a voting trustee to holdTime stock.   Time is fighting Paramount's $200-a-share bid while trying topreserve a planned merger with Warner Communications Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Net withdrawals from savings and loaninstitutions slowed by more than 50 percent in May to $2.4 billion,the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said.   After counting interest credited to depositors' accounts, totaldeposits in the nation's 2,934 Sandamp;Ls grew by $587 million during Mayto $955.2 billion, the agency said Thursday. It was the firstincrease since last December.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Environmental Protection Agency ordered aban on most remaining uses of cancer-causing asbestos, forbiddingits use in hundreds of products ranging from automobile brake partsto water pipes.   The prohibition announced Thursday will be phased in over thenext seven years and apply only to new products. Asbestos-containingproducts already in use _ and not affected by previous restrictions_ are not included because in some cases replacement might be morehazardous than a gradual phase-out, officials said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Coffee drinkers could be the winners of apossible marketing war among roasters following this week'ssuspension of coffee bean export quotas, analysts say.   The International Coffee Organization's decision to suspendquotas will enable smaller coffee producing countries severelyrestricted under the quota system to export high-quality coffeebeans to willing U.S. customers, observers said Thursday. It alsocould mean lower retail prices by year's end.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush has cancelled the debt ofsub-Saharan African countries to the United States.   The president said at a news conference Thursday that beginningOct. 1, the U.S. government will forgive official development loansin the sub-Saharan countries. In 1987, the most recent year in whichfigures were immediately available, the State Department put thetotal of U.S. loans to sub-Saharan Africa at $4.3 billion, including$743 million in development loans, $1.5 billion from the U.S.government's Export-Import Bank and $1.2 billion in U.S. governmentloans to buy surplus American farm products.   Bush did not say which of these categories would be included.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market eked out its third straight gain in anotherquiet session Thursday as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrialsrose 5.88 to 2,462.44.   The dollar closed narrowly higher against all key currencies.   Bond prices rebounded amid further signs that the Federal Reservemight be easing monetary policy and pushing interest rates lower.   Raw coffee futures prices slid to 8-year lows; sugar futures fellsharply for the second straight day; energy futures fell; porkfutures continued to retreat; grains and soybeans were mixed; andprecious metals were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>